<br>
for a long time, psychiatrists have actually thought that this was 'denial' and a bad thing to do.  but i've read of a study which basically pointed out that people who kept themselves busy and didn't sink down into despair actually coped better in the end, because they were eventually able to deal with their grief and move beyond it.  whereas, many of the people who were allowed to voice their grief kept wallowing and never got over it.<br>
<br>
so, my advice is:  try to maintain, but give yourself room.  if you're going to be sad, don't let anyone belittle you over it.  but also remember that the sadness IS going to pass, and you don't have to stay in it forever.<br>
<br>
my sympathies are with you... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unikirose.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nikirose</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://NoirDaila.homestead.com/files/Laney/america.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/2/02 1:33:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=588.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.extremezone.com/~medieval/buttons/bloodsword.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: When loved ones die.</span><hr size=1> Thank you Luna,<br>
